{
  "id": "phekb-crohns-disease-biologic-disambig",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "crohns-disease",
  "name": "Crohn's Disease - Biologic Disambiguation via _has (Cross-Indication Filter)",
  "description": "**Cross-resource _has test.** Anti-TNF biologics like infliximab and adalimumab are used for BOTH Crohn's disease AND rheumatoid arthritis. A naive MedicationRequest query for these biologics returns the union of Crohn's + RA patients. This test exercises the FHIR `_has` reverse chaining parameter to find patients who have a Crohn's diagnosis AND a biologic prescription \u2014 filtering out RA patients on the same biologics. This is the classic disambiguation problem solved by combining evidence at the patient level.",
  "prompt": "Find patients who have a Crohn's disease diagnosis AND are prescribed an anti-TNF biologic (infliximab or adalimumab) or other Crohn's biologic (ustekinumab). The point is to identify Crohn's patients on biologic therapy \u2014 not rheumatoid arthritis patients on the same biologics.",
  "prompts": {
    "naive": "Find Crohn's patients on biologics.",
    "broad": "Find patients who have BOTH a Crohn's disease diagnosis AND a biologic medication prescription. Anti-TNF biologics (infliximab, adalimumab) are also used in rheumatoid arthritis, so the Crohn's diagnosis is required to disambiguate. Use FHIR `_has` (reverse chaining) to combine evidence from Condition + MedicationRequest at the patient level.",
    "expert": "I need patients who match TWO criteria simultaneously: a Condition with a Crohn's SNOMED code (34000006, 7620006, 196977009, 1197732001, 1197733006) AND a MedicationRequest with a Crohn's biologic RxNorm code (191831 infliximab, 327361 adalimumab, 847083 ustekinumab). Use FHIR `_has` parameter on the Patient resource: `Patient?_has:Condition:patient:code=...&_has:MedicationRequest:patient:code=...`. The double `_has` ensures both conditions are met for the same patient (intersection, not union)."
  },
